> > 1       h         30     0.1097     0.1526     0.0279
> > 1       l         30    -0.3757     0.4185     0.0764
> > 1       m         30    -0.1309     0.2820     0.0515
> > 
> > and A1.items:
> > 
> > accurate        description
> > accurate        publicity
> > accurate        use
> > 
> > from which I assume that the nouns for a given adjective are presented in 
> > the order high-low-medium (the h-l-m ordering is consistent through 
> > A1.means). There's no file that explicitly matches items and frequency 
> > bands. But the fact that I'm getting very bad correlations for the 
> > adjective data and good correlations with the other datasets makes me 
> > think that I'm aligning items and scores wrong.
> 
> The order is high-low-medium. Going back to the original BNC counts
> confirms this (the adjective noun pairs were selected from the BNC).
>  
> 63 accurate description
> 1 accurate publicity
> 5 accurate use
> 
> > Table 2 on page 5 of Keller and Lapata (2003) does give examples for the 
> > various frequency bands; for example "hungry animal" is high, "hungry 
> > pleasure" is medium and "hungry application" is low. In A1.items, these 
> > are presented in the following order:
> > 
> > hungry  animal
> > hungry  pleasure
> > hungry  application
> > 
> > i.e. high-medium-low. On the other hand the items for "naughty" are 
> > presented high-low-medium. The examples given in Table 2 for "guilty" are 
> > "verdict" (high), "secret" (medium) and "cat" (low), but in A1.items we have:
> > 
> > guilty  verdict
> > guilty  cat
> > guilty  feeling
> > 
> > i.e high, low and an item that doesn't appear in the table at all.
> 
> This is an error in the paper. The BNC frequencies are:
> 
> 6 hungry animal
> 1 hungry pleasure
> 4 hungry application
> 
> > In short, I don't think I have the information that's necessary to use the 
> > A1 and A2 datasets. I'll be extremely grateful if you can help me with 
> > this - it may make the difference between my being able to submit to ACL 
> > or not.
> 
> Note that the order for the verb and noun files is high-medium-low.
> I'm including the BNC counts for the seen ones.
